split envelope in key, body and headers.

the headers will have a pretty recurring size, where as the body is totally unpredictable.
since the headers are signed, the sender can be verified before proceeding. after that the mimetype, which can be pretty well trusted can be evaluated.
if its a movie, which isnt supported it can be rejected before unpacking gigs of data.
the size should be included in the headers, maybe.
MimeType and Size cant be trusted, but you might trust them, if you trust the actor.

This should avoid resource starcation ddos vectors from unknown actors.
it should also alleviate dijudication of the content and if and how it should be dispatched.

Obviously headers are used "everywhere" and is good practise. Splitting them out in an encrypted field of its own - with a size limit - makes evaluating the incoming message much more stable.
